    * Lazy Link Renderer

A custom LinkResolver which tries to circumvent the PageManager.getPage() for each link in the page to be rendered.
Only follows the link on a page when clicked on it, opposite to the way we deal with it. Renders links and verifying their validating when loading the page - use of pre-rendered body content, because rendering of wiki pages is quite slow.

{quote}
When I first found out that every page is basically rendered from markup to html every time it is displayed, I got a bad feeling about the efficiency of such an implementation.

Have you ever considered splitting a page internally into static and dynamic fragments. When you think about it, all the basic wiki markup doesn't change dynamically and could be cached. On the other hand, there are macros that must be executed each time a page is rendered and thus can't be cached. But there are also macros that render the same stuff over and over (e.g. {{toc}}, {{noformat}}, {{code}}, etc) and if these had a configuration setting that would tell the renderer that the output can be cached and reused, then you could skip a lot of marco invocations. To make this caching really efficient, the plugins should be able to define the cache expiration policy (never, after X minutes/seconds).

I know that there is the {cache} macro that could do something similar, but that macro must be applied by users (which often don't know or care about these things) and more importantly suffers from a security hole that bypasses Confluence's ACL system and can expose content to users that should not have access to it.
{quote}

